segments.text: Did you have any favorite instructors during your student days?
Yes, D.B.
Cofer was one in English, and my freshman English, I got credit for that, but I had to take a one-hour lecture course that was called
contemporary civilization, I believe it was, that, not F.L., but Thomas, who was in the engineering, I mean the English department, taught.
I enjoyed that.
Probably one who really didn't have a course on him, but took a visit to course, was Fritz Hensel.
and Nestor McGinnis.
Now they were off in landscape architecture and floriculture, but I was interested in that too.
And being a regular, because I had credit for this English, each year I was able to take one or two courses extra of something that I was particularly interested in.
So I took Nestor McGinnis and Hensel's course in landscape ornamentals.
And Dr. F. E. Giesecke, I was very fond of him.
He had been here many years earlier as head of the engineering drawing department and then migrated to the University of Texas as the head of their architecture department.
My junior year, I believe it was, he returned to A&M as head of the department of architecture, college architect, and director of the engineering experiment station.
I worked very close with him my senior year particularly and then for quite a number of years afterwards and employed at the university or college at that time.
Si Sanston was another one I enjoyed.
I had to have a course over in the civil engineering department in engineering contracts and law.
What did the students do for entertainment and recreation?
I think I might preface this by a statement made by a brother of mine.
My next younger brother came to A&M after he graduated.
No, I've got my brothers mixed up.
My youngest brother came to A&M one year and he got

so strongly in love that he dropped out that year and married and wound up in the Corps of Engineers and then later was inducted into the Army and after the war he came back and decided to go back to school and he looked at the University of Texas and looked at A&M and then when he was visiting over here with me later we were walking across the campus and I made some comment about I think we had
orange no parking signs painted on the curbs.
And I mentioned to him that the students one time refused to go to class because they had to pass over these orange painted signs.
And he says, well, that's the difference between the University of Texas and A&M.
They have something to do over in Austin.
And over at A&M, they've got to make their entertainment and pleasures out of whatever they can find around here.
Well, there wasn't a lot to do at A&M, in the social end, really.
Wednesday nights and Saturday nights, I had a picture show in Assembly Hall, which was on the site of the present chapel.
This was built during the First World War.
It was a wooden stucco building.
So almost everybody could rake up 10 cents or 15 cents.
Usually went to the movie at night, Wednesday night and Saturday night.
Freshmen had an interesting sideline for Saturday night because it was custom then, at least in the fall semester, for freshmen to air out.
after the theater, after the showing there.
By airing out, this meant they had to leave the dormitory and go out anywhere they could find a place and spend the night sleeping out in the woods.
I remember the first Saturday night I had on the campus.
For some reason or other, I took out toward the east, which was down at that time back in the horse barns where the
system administration building is now, and found a farm back over there that was growing watermelons.
So I had a watermelon to settle my stomach that night before I tried to bed down in the patch out there somewhere to sleep.
eased back in the dormitory somewhere between 2 and 3 o'clock in the morning when most everyone had gone to sleep.
But this was a common thing for Saturday nights, the upperclassmen airing out the fish.
And Sunday afternoons, the big event was to go down and see the Southern Pacific train come in.
In the early part of the year, quite often on Sundays, particularly good weather,

fish band or a fish group including some musical instruments and the rest armed with brooms had the job of going down and to the railroad station and sweeping out the train much to the dismay and surprise of the passengers on the train but while it was here they went in and swept out the train not to say the dismay of the railroad of course they usually
wore some outlandish costume.
They were not in full uniform.
And other things, you might wander around and take a hike around in the woods.
Some of the ponds, there used to be a lake down in what was called College Park.
That's in the corner of Jersey and Weldon Road.
Well, Jersey and Dexter, yes, in that corner.
College Park, that was the only area that there were any private homes at that time, and there were a few there.
But there was a lake in there that later was drained during the predominance of malaria in this area.
Well, that was, I take it, a privately owned lake?
It was owned by the Southside Development Company, who was a real estate organization of a number of faculty people.
Dan Scotes was head of ag engineering, and I started to call him Wheezy Clark.
That was his name, common name.
Dr. F.B.
Clark was a member of it.
I can't think of his name.
His wife is still alive, a little chemistry prof at the sector.
A number of the college staff had gone together to try to set up some place where a person might build a home.
And they had built a number of what were called company homes that they rented to faculty people.
Was there a swimming pool in the basement of the Y?
There was a swimming pool in the basement of the Y, that's right.
This was after the P.L.
Downs Auditorium was built.
The YMCA floored it over and put a bowling alley there first and then had a few billiard tables.
You might go to the Y on the weekend and play some billiards or go swimming in the small indoor pool.
And of course, the big activity, of course, were all the various balls that were held on the campus.
And many times, the entire main dining room and annex of the Speza Hall were just packed and jammed with participants.
At that time, of course, people danced with each other, arm to arm or body to body, or what you might call it.
The poor girl who danced more than ten steps or so with one chap thought she was a wallflower, maybe.
Because there were, of course, a predominance of stags there, but many of them were programmed dances.
And the big balls, of course, were the football weekends and the Ross volunteer dances in the spring area.
Was the RV hop only open to members of the RVs?
They usually had their activities seemed like three days.
I was not an RV and at one or two of those dances I believe they permitted others to come.
Then of course we had the big Bozar Ball which is the architectural club's annual dance and all of these dances
There were usually very extensive decorations erected in the main ballroom of Sabeza Hall.
And of course the dance after the Thanksgiving game was usually almost impossible because it was so thick you could hardly move in that time.
I would imagine you had former students as well as students there.
Texas and A&M and everybody, anybody wanted to go and want those and all you had to do was have the price of the ticket to get in those dances.
And then of course the various military organizations had their dances and some of the other clubs.
And then there was the staff and faculty dances about once a month I guess.
And occasionally we had
entertainment series, anything from an opera up and down in Guyon Hall.
Of course, these were never, you know, more than four or five of them a year.
Of course, on Sunday morning you had a march in the chapel, which was compulsory at that time.
And that was in Guyon?
That was in Guyon Hall.
The old chapel was discontinued.
It was a chapel after Guyon Hall was erected in what, 1920, somewhere in there?
18, I believe.
And the old chapel became the armory for many years.
It was the armory when I was here.
And I have a small rifle range in there, a little range.
This was later moved to a metal shed down on the side of the present laundry.
There was a laundry, it was west of the laundry because it was discontinued, because the bullet stops in there got worn in and a stray bullet or two went through the laundry, so they shut that down.
That would be a factor, wouldn't it?
I bought her plate in there for stopping the bullets, but after they shot so many times in the same place.
Did you have any student theatrical groups or anything of that nature to put on plays or was that a later development?
I don't remember any at all.
We had not an actor's club, there was a scribbler's club that
Tommy Mayo and Dr. Summey particularly in the English department sponsored.
I wasn't much a writer, but I enjoyed going to the meetings.
But I don't think there were any dramatic things.
Now there was, at that time we had the Greek Club, the forerunner of the singing cadets.
Our principal job under the
direction of the band director then, Richard Dunn, later called Colonel Dunn.
We sang for chapel services on Sunday morning.
That's about all we tried.
The Scribblers Club did what?
Oh, it was a club that those people who were interested in trying to write a little and studying various writings,
And as I say, Dr. and Ms. Summey were particular sponsors of that club.
There were lots of clubs, of course, different as they are now, and different both organizations, hometown clubs, and some along the educational lines.
I did a little checking in your senior Longhorn, and there was an indication that you were a member of the Dome Club.

Well, the dome club, that was so called because the senior architectural students in the engineering phase of architecture had their drafting tables and classes up in the unfinished dome of the academic building, the old main building.
So we were members of the Dome Club.
It really wasn't a formal organization, except that meant you spent most of your senior year up in the Dome.
So that would have been seniors in architecture.
Right.
We know that a goodly number of students at various times had jobs of one type or another on campus.
Did you have any jobs while you were a student?
I had two particular jobs.
One of them for a while I worked for Missouri Pacific Railroad as a night clerk.
My job was mainly to take off the mail and the baggage
trunks and things that came in during the night and put them in the warehouse at the station.
I remember one afternoon I was on duty though, and I had a rather unexpected job.
A horse came in by express in a crate.
And for a while I was at loss how I was going to get that horse out of the baggage car, but we managed.
I guess the biggest thing, though, was unloading a bale of cotton by myself one night.
I don't know why it came in, but there's many unexpected things were coming in because of research activities.
You'd normally get it at a freight station instead of coming in by express.
Then my senior year, I worked, well, I worked this preceding summer
At A&M, before our junior and senior years, architecture students had to come back to A&M three weeks early to take summer practice in architecture.
And I remember the first year I worked on the side, the Ag Experiment Station needed some people to pick cotton.
Well, this wasn't ordinary picking.
You were paid by the hour and not by the pound, and you picked the bowls off each stalk of it.
put them in a separate sack because they were working on some genetics problem.
Then my senior year I was taking a course in mechanical equipment of buildings under Dr. Gieske who was very prominent in the field of heating, ventilating, air conditioning.
And he had some curves that he had published in some paper.
He gave us three pence for

computing the friction head in pipes when you're sizing your hot water heating systems, and this paper is rather old and deteriorated, so one day I made a tracing, redrew this on tracing cloth and made a bunch of blueprints and passed them on among my classmates.
One day Dr. Kiewski saw some student, I believe it was George Glover, using one of these and he wanted to know where he got it.
And he said, well, Howard Badgett made it.
So his having seen that, he rather liked the work I did, I guess.
He offered me a job of illustrating Experiment Station bulletins that he and Mr. E.W.
Steele, who was head of the Municipal and Sanitary Engineering Department at the time, and books or papers Dr. Gieske had written, asked me to draw the illustrations from them.
So this really led to my staying with A&M after graduation.
Like during my senior year, one day Dr. Gieske asked me, would I like to take graduate work?
I said, well, I'd always been interested in a lot of courses.
Of course, that was my idea of graduate work then.
You'd pick out a bunch of courses you liked and take.
So I said, yes.
He said he thought he'd give me a scholarship, and he did.
He got a Portland cement fellowship that I did my graduate work on in research and mechanical equipment of buildings.
And following the completion of that year, well, he offered me a job with the Engineering Experiment Station at A&M.
And you stayed with them for?
I stayed with the Engineering Experiment Station until I went on active duty during World War II in October 1940.
What types of things did you do for the Experiment Station?
We were studying to determine the loss of head, the friction head.
in new types of fittings that had come out then.
Mueller Rice Company and some of the other rice and copper companies had developed copper pipe and fittings called sweat fittings.
Streamline was the trade name.
And they had no known friction head losses for these.
We did a lot of work in that field.
We did work in
studying the comfort zone in air conditioning in conjunction with the American Society of Heating and Ventilating Engineers.
They had a comfort zone chart which they had prepared up in the north and the east.
This is a combination of temperature, humidity, and air movement in which various areas of people are comfortable in.
But they weren't sure that this would apply all over the country.
So we set up a laboratory at A&M to make a comparative study to see if there was any difference in people's reaction to various conditions here than in the east.
We did quite a bit of work on initial early work on what was called panel warming.
which had been developed in England and Germany, where you had pipes through your floor at that time, concrete floors usually, and passed warm water through it to get radiant heating.
And we did a lot of work in cast iron fittings.
Friction losses were computed in those days and we did some actual experiments to measure the loss of various velocities of water flow.
We did quite a bit of work that time also in various methods and phases of what is now called waste water treatment, sewage treatment.
There was, Dr. Gieske, as I said, was a combination of, his combination included college architect.
There was not a building or a project on the campus that he had charge of that didn't include some type of experiment in building construction.
So generally we were setting up something of that sort, I remember, down in the chemistry
building, the first wing, which was built by the university, by the college then, rather than contract work.
We measured the settlement of the building as the soil compacted from the weight of the building.
Under the tower, which has since been removed on the old Petroleum Geology Building, which included the Engineering Experiment Station in there too,
We put soil pressure cells under the footings of the tower in order to study the pressure bulb, the distribution of pressure under a footing.
In a sense, you made the whole campus a laboratory.
This is very much the way Dr. Gieske worked.
There wasn't anything he did that wasn't an experiment or to prove or disprove some assumption or fact.
Well, in his position as head of the engineering experiment station, he was obligated to experiment.
And as college architect, he was responsible for all the building construction.
As college architect, did he also design the buildings?
Oh, yes.
He had an architectural staff, which Phil Norton, an A.M. graduate, was his chief, I won't say engineer, chief architect, but he was in charge basically of the day-to-day operation of the office.
And then in the early 30s, 32, 34, and 5, when we,

got a bit of money for expansion, at which time the Ag Engineering Building, the System Administration, the Petroleum Geology, the Veterinary Science Building Group, the Animal Industries Building, and some others were erected.
Rather than farm out the work to architects over the country, the board agreed that the

college was set up of its own architectural engineering office and at that time we had we inherited Ross Hall which had been condemned my senior year in 1929 as a dormitory because they thought it was going to fall in and we tied it up with a few tie bars through the building and things and used it for many years thereafter but this building was largely
architects, engineers, and other things there who designed these buildings.
Prior to that, the office designed the initial stadium, a section of the concrete stadium which was erected in about 1930, I think it started.
And Hart Hall, Walton Hall,
The library, original Cushing Library, was designed by that office.
That was the early office before the expansion for the 33 group.
You said the college got a little bit of money.
What was the source of this money?
I think it was the beginning of the oil money, I believe.
That would be from the University Available Fund?
University Available Fund.
I believe that was the source of it.
I don't know where they got so much.
You made mention of a 33 group.
Well, these were designed and built in 1932, 34, and 5.
So you had a half a dozen.
You had the System Administration Building, the Ag Engineering Building, the Veterinary Science Group, which is now Civil Engineering, the Animal Industries Building,
second wing of the chemistry building.
What else?
Well, the library was started in 1929.
The library was built on the site of the old chemistry building where Dr. Harrington
was one of my freshman chemistry profs.
I had my chemistry lab there.
This was demolished in the summer of 1930.

I remember very well a classmate of mine who had difficulty in chemistry and told me he wanted to be sure and get his brick out of that building because he had flunked chemistry one time and he wanted a brick.
So I got him a brick out of that building.
Oh, I know what I was going to say.
In capacity of designing the buildings that we've just been talking about, did the college architect's office also do, well, I'll call it the decorative designing for the exterior?
I did the complete building.
In the big expansion in the early 30s,
architect named Sam Vosper who did the primary design and detailed so much of the work that was done on these buildings.
He followed largely a lot of the old architectural styles, but he brought it up to date by making these

using common things for instance in the veterinary science building some of the decorative moldings and things were horse heads or cow heads or pig heads or such as that he tried to make in the building in the decoration something that was indicative of the type of
activity was to go on in the building.

He did all the original work along with his helpers of course and one of them at that time was Elo Urmanoski who has been quite prominent up at Texas Tech in their landscape floor culture department for many years.
They designed
system administration building.
In fact, at that time when we used artificial stone, the artificial stone was made on the campus here.
We set up a stone plan around and then one of the, on the system building, the stone was made right about where the Texas flag is now, cast for that building.
